00:00:45.140 --> 00:00:48.260
from the cookbook, which I
had the pleasure of reviewing

00:00:48.260 --> 00:00:49.260
in full detail.

00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:51.500
I was talking to her earlier.

00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:53.900
I get a lot of cookbooks
that come past me, obviously,

00:00:53.900 --> 00:00:55.100
being on the food team.

00:00:55.100 --> 00:00:56.850
And this is one of the
most exciting books

00:00:56.850 --> 00:00:59.540
that I've seen in a long time,
because it talks about so

00:00:59.540 --> 00:01:01.550
many unique ingredients
that you see often

00:01:01.550 --> 00:01:02.840
on shelves and markets--

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:04.470
farmers markets, et cetera.

00:01:04.470 --> 00:01:05.960
And she's done
such an amazing job

00:01:05.960 --> 00:01:08.270
in making such a very
approachable book,

00:01:08.270 --> 00:01:10.370
to look at these
ingredients in a way that

00:01:10.370 --> 00:01:12.882
are so simple to
execute but so tasty

00:01:12.882 --> 00:01:14.840
and really highlight the
deliciousness of them.

00:01:14.840 --> 00:01:16.400
So congratulations.

00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:19.030
So a quick intro, and
then we'll get let

00:01:19.030 --> 00:01:20.330
her get into the good stuff.

00:01:20.330 --> 00:01:24.050
So it's my pleasure to
introduce Laura McLively, who

00:01:24.050 --> 00:01:28.520
has authored the "Berkeley Bowl
Cookbook," which celebrates

00:01:28.520 --> 00:01:32.630
the unfamiliar yet extraordinary
produce of California's most

00:01:32.630 --> 00:01:35.080
iconic market--
the Berkeley Bowl.

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:38.535
The cookbook offers
recipes on a variety

00:01:38.535 --> 00:01:40.160
of fruits and
vegetables, some of which

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:43.250
she's brought with her to kind
of pass around and play with,

00:01:43.250 --> 00:01:46.380
that are really largely
overlooked in popular cuisine.

00:01:46.380 --> 00:01:49.080
I think as culinarians,
as home chefs and chefs,

00:01:49.080 --> 00:01:50.874
we really get focused
on ingredients

00:01:50.874 --> 00:01:52.040
that we're so familiar with.

00:01:52.040 --> 00:01:54.050
And what's really
unique about this book

00:01:54.050 --> 00:01:56.540
is you're able to take a
dive into some ingredients

00:01:56.540 --> 00:01:58.280
that maybe you haven't
seen for a while,

00:01:58.280 --> 00:02:01.190
or execute them in a way
that maybe you haven't

00:02:01.190 --> 00:02:02.570
seen before in the past.

00:02:02.570 --> 00:02:06.200
So Laura is a registered
dietitian, an avid home cook,

00:02:06.200 --> 00:02:09.110
creator of the popular
blog, "My Berkeley Bowl."

00:02:09.110 --> 00:02:12.770
And she's created recipes from
really the unfamiliar aspects

00:02:12.770 --> 00:02:15.980
of the exotic fruits and
vegetables within the market.

00:02:15.980 --> 00:02:18.840
The market has easily
over 1,000 vegetables

00:02:18.840 --> 00:02:20.720
and produce items out there.

00:02:20.720 --> 00:02:22.880
And she's taken those
hand-selected ones

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:26.101
that she feels are the
most unique and overlooked.

00:02:26.101 --> 00:02:28.100
Some of the ingredients--
or some of the recipes

00:02:28.100 --> 00:02:30.050
that you'll actually
see in the book,

00:02:30.050 --> 00:02:31.520
that I thought were
super exciting,

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:34.100
were things like the
kiwano melon cooler,

00:02:34.100 --> 00:02:36.830
the falafel waffles with
Armenian cucumber slaw,

00:02:36.830 --> 00:02:39.110
or the burdock root pizza.

