00:03:10.910 --> 00:03:14.049
because I'm sure moments
will come up where I can talk

00:03:14.049 --> 00:03:16.340
a little bit more about my
inspiration behind the book,

00:03:16.340 --> 00:03:18.070
but you're here to
see a cooking demo,

00:03:18.070 --> 00:03:20.250
so we're just going
to get started.

00:03:20.250 --> 00:03:22.730
The first dish that we're
going to make is a beverage.

00:03:22.730 --> 00:03:24.740
It's called shiso limeade.

00:03:24.740 --> 00:03:28.300
And there's various
kinds of shiso.

00:03:28.300 --> 00:03:31.010
So actually, this from the
Google garden right here.

00:03:31.010 --> 00:03:33.770
This is red shiso.

00:03:33.770 --> 00:03:36.610
And you also grow
the green shiso.

00:03:36.610 --> 00:03:40.920
And the one that we're using
today is called Chinese shiso.

00:03:40.920 --> 00:03:42.630
So you have to be
kind of careful

00:03:42.630 --> 00:03:44.546
when you're going to
make this recipe that you

00:03:44.546 --> 00:03:47.515
are sure you are identifying
the right kind of shiso.

00:03:47.515 --> 00:03:49.795
So Chinese shiso
looks like this.

00:03:49.795 --> 00:03:53.680
It's a leaf that's commonly
used in Japanese cuisine.

00:03:53.680 --> 00:03:57.390
And it's-- you're going to
look for kind of a heart-shaped

00:03:57.390 --> 00:03:57.890
leaf.

00:03:57.890 --> 00:04:02.090
It's two tones-- the green on
top, and purple on the bottom.

00:04:02.090 --> 00:04:07.450
So you might have seen shiso
before when you order sushi.

00:04:07.450 --> 00:04:10.730
It sometimes comes on the plate
with the wasabi on top of it.

00:04:10.730 --> 00:04:13.260
But a lot of people don't know
that you can actually eat it.

00:04:13.260 --> 00:04:15.385
So today I'm going show
you one of my favorite ways

00:04:15.385 --> 00:04:17.880
to prepare shiso, which
is in this limeade.

00:04:17.880 --> 00:04:20.959
So I actually came across
this recipe by mistake.

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:24.180
I knew I wanted to serve
shiso as a beverage

00:04:24.180 --> 00:04:28.250
because it kind of has this
refreshing, lemony, herbal,

00:04:28.250 --> 00:04:31.800
minty scent, but a really
nice earthy undertone.

00:04:31.800 --> 00:04:34.490
And so I thought, well, that
would make a really great tea.

00:04:34.490 --> 00:04:38.460
So I boiled my water,
and I went ahead

00:04:38.460 --> 00:04:39.630
and added the leaves to it.

00:04:39.630 --> 00:04:40.921
So we're just going to do that.

00:04:40.921 --> 00:04:42.340
It's really simple.

00:04:42.340 --> 00:04:44.060
It's this hot water.

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:48.570
And I let it steep for
about 15 to 30 minutes

00:04:48.570 --> 00:04:52.110
so that that shiso flavor
really infuses the water.

00:04:52.110 --> 00:04:55.560
And so this is what it looks
like after 15, 30 minutes.

00:04:55.560 --> 00:04:58.880
And so I took the leaves out.

00:04:58.880 --> 00:05:02.392
Usually you just strain them,
but for the sake of the demo,

00:05:02.392 --> 00:05:04.260
we're just going
to use some tongs.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:13.966
And you can see that
the water is clear.

00:05:13.966 --> 00:05:15.709
It comes out like a clear tea.

00:05:15.709 --> 00:05:18.250
And I tried it, and I thought,
well, that's really delicious,

00:05:18.250 --> 00:05:20.000
but I can't really put
that in a cookbook,

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:23.509
like "add leaves to water"
and, call that a cookbook.

00:05:23.509 --> 00:05:25.300
So I was like, what am
I going to do to it?

00:05:25.300 --> 00:05:28.870
So I thought maybe I'll chill it
and I'll add some lime juice so

00:05:28.870 --> 00:05:31.280
that it's kind of like a
refreshing non-alcoholic

00:05:31.280 --> 00:05:32.000
beverage.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.050
And this was one of those really
rare moments in the kitchen--

00:05:36.050 --> 00:05:37.756
or actually it's not so rare.

00:05:37.756 --> 00:05:40.130
This is one of those special
moments in the kitchen, when

00:05:40.130 --> 00:05:42.410
you're playing around with
foods and you discover

00:05:42.410 --> 00:05:44.869
something exciting and magical.

00:05:44.869 --> 00:05:46.160
So I'll show you what happened.

00:05:46.160 --> 00:05:48.160
So I added the lime juice.

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:52.540
And it turned this bright
pink color, like bubblegum.

00:05:52.540 --> 00:05:55.280
So I had no idea this would
happen, and I was just like,

00:05:55.280 --> 00:05:57.994
oh, my god, this has
to go in the cookbook.

00:05:57.994 --> 00:06:02.130
So we just sweeten it with
a little agave nectar.

00:06:02.130 --> 00:06:03.950
And that's it.

00:06:03.950 --> 00:06:06.330
And so you're just going
to serve this on ice.

00:06:06.330 --> 00:06:11.140
And it's so nice to
serve this at a barbecue

00:06:11.140 --> 00:06:14.150
or party at your house as a
nice, non-alcoholic option

00:06:14.150 --> 00:06:17.030
because people expect
it to be pink lemonade,

00:06:17.030 --> 00:06:19.880
and then you can kind of
see on their faces they're

00:06:19.880 --> 00:06:22.860
surprised by this
flavor in the background

00:06:22.860 --> 00:06:24.235
that they don't
really recognize.

00:06:24.235 --> 00:06:25.730
And so that's shiso.

00:06:25.730 --> 00:06:29.864
So we'll just pour
ourselves a little glass.

00:06:29.864 --> 00:06:32.420
And it's nice to
garnish it with--

00:06:32.420 --> 00:06:34.410
I shouldn't have put
all the leaves in there.

00:06:34.410 --> 00:06:37.766
It's nice to garnish it
with some leaves and maybe

00:06:37.766 --> 00:06:38.811
a slice of lime.

00:06:43.421 --> 00:06:46.690
So you can see, it just
has such a beautiful color.

00:06:46.690 --> 00:06:49.610
And kids really like it too.

00:06:49.610 --> 00:06:53.380
I just had a Memorial Day
barbecue, and I served this.

00:06:53.380 --> 00:06:56.910
And the kids had, like, no
idea that it was this weirdo

00:06:56.910 --> 00:06:59.631
herb that they never tried.

00:06:59.631 --> 00:07:01.222
So there you go--

00:07:01.222 --> 00:07:03.030
shiso limeade.

00:07:03.030 --> 00:07:05.530
So as you can see,
something like shiso

00:07:05.530 --> 00:07:08.000
that maybe you'd pass
at the grocery store,

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.340
or you've seen it at the
farmer's market, you're like,

00:07:10.340 --> 00:07:13.259
well, I don't know that it is,
I don't know what to do with it.

00:07:13.259 --> 00:07:15.550
What you find when you start
to bring these things home

00:07:15.550 --> 00:07:18.495
is that they're not as
intimidating as they look.

00:07:18.495 --> 00:07:19.870
And so the thing
I really learned

00:07:19.870 --> 00:07:21.661
in working with these
fruits and vegetables

00:07:21.661 --> 00:07:25.120
is that what's maybe
new to me and kind

00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:29.000
of foreign and intimidating
is as normal to someone else

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:31.700
as apples and
potatoes are for me.

00:07:31.700 --> 00:07:33.250
And we should find out why.

00:07:33.250 --> 00:07:34.940
There's probably a
really good reason

00:07:34.940 --> 00:07:39.650
why it's normal to maybe someone
in another part of the country

00:07:39.650 --> 00:07:41.840
or another part of the world.

00:07:41.840 --> 00:07:44.604
So shiso is one of those foods.

00:07:44.604 --> 00:07:50.016
And so let me just move
this out of the way.

00:07:50.016 --> 00:07:51.000
Thank you.

00:07:55.428 --> 00:07:56.910
Thanks.

00:07:56.910 --> 00:07:58.930
I brought some other
fruits and ve--

00:07:58.930 --> 00:08:00.230
we're going to prepare
a couple other dishes,

00:08:00.230 --> 00:08:02.521
but I brought some things
that I found at Berkeley Bowl

00:08:02.521 --> 00:08:04.730
last night, that
I thought we could

00:08:04.730 --> 00:08:07.820
play a little identification
game together.

00:08:07.820 --> 00:08:14.335
So here's some of them.

00:08:14.335 --> 00:08:16.910
So has anyone seen this before?

00:08:16.910 --> 00:08:17.907
OK, great.

00:08:17.907 --> 00:08:18.740
What is this called?

00:08:18.740 --> 00:08:19.797
AUDIENCE: Rambutan.

00:08:19.797 --> 00:08:20.880
LAURA MCLIVELY: All right.

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:23.510
So does anybody know why
it's called rambutan?

00:08:23.510 --> 00:08:24.860
What "rambut" means?

00:08:24.860 --> 00:08:26.832
Take a guess.

00:08:26.832 --> 00:08:27.720
AUDIENCE: Hairs.

00:08:27.720 --> 00:08:28.360
LAURA MCLIVELY: Hairs, yeah.

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:29.990
Rambut means "hair"
in Malaysian.

00:08:29.990 --> 00:08:31.620
So that's why this
is called that.

00:08:31.620 --> 00:08:35.940
In the book, the recipe for
this is you just cut around

00:08:35.940 --> 00:08:37.110
this and take off the top.

00:08:37.110 --> 00:08:38.539
And there's a lychee-like
fruit in the middle.

00:08:38.539 --> 00:08:40.109
And you dip these
in white chocolate

00:08:40.109 --> 00:08:42.090
and dust them with
a little clove.

00:08:42.090 --> 00:08:44.410
It's a really simple
recipe to enjoy something

00:08:44.410 --> 00:08:47.450
that looks really crazy.

00:08:47.450 --> 00:08:50.400
Does anyone know what this is?

00:08:50.400 --> 00:08:51.136
AUDIENCE: Cacao?

00:08:51.136 --> 00:08:52.260
LAURA MCLIVELY: Good guess.

00:08:52.260 --> 00:08:53.520
Not cacao.

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:54.520
AUDIENCE: Banana flower.

00:08:54.520 --> 00:08:56.353
LAURA MCLIVELY: Banana
flower, that's right.

00:08:56.353 --> 00:09:00.770
So these are little baby
bananas, not yet born.

00:09:00.770 --> 00:09:04.400
So these, you can take
off these outer petals

00:09:04.400 --> 00:09:06.550
and save them as a serving dish.

00:09:06.550 --> 00:09:08.980
And then there's a core
in it that's sort of

00:09:08.980 --> 00:09:10.560
like an artichoke heart.

00:09:10.560 --> 00:09:14.290
And so you can slice that
up, and in this recipe

00:09:14.290 --> 00:09:15.750
it's stir fried
with glass noodles,

00:09:15.750 --> 00:09:18.055
and then you serve in the petal.

00:09:18.055 --> 00:09:19.890
So we'll do a couple
more of these later,

00:09:19.890 --> 00:09:21.881
but we'll probably
want to move on.

00:09:25.320 --> 00:09:29.614
OK, so I should mention too
that the cookbook is organized--

00:09:29.614 --> 00:09:32.400
the chapters are organized
by the type of plant

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:34.620
it is, or the part of the plant.

00:09:34.620 --> 00:09:38.400
So for instance, the shiso
is out of the Leaves chapter.

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:41.330
And then next, we're going to
be doing sea beans and soba out

00:09:41.330 --> 00:09:43.184
of the Succulents chapter.

00:09:43.184 --> 00:09:45.600
And the reason we did that is
because when you're shopping

00:09:45.600 --> 00:09:47.700
at a store like Berkeley
Bowl, or when you're

00:09:47.700 --> 00:09:51.360
shopping at your farmer's market
or at the local ethnic grocery,

00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:54.120
usually it's an
ingredient-centric shopping

00:09:54.120 --> 00:09:54.810
experience.

00:09:54.810 --> 00:09:57.195
You're not there saying,
like, I'm going to make this.

00:09:57.195 --> 00:09:59.610
You go, and you wait
to see what you find,

00:09:59.610 --> 00:10:02.080
and then you develop
a meal around it.

00:10:02.080 --> 00:10:05.070
And so I really wanted
the book to be organized

00:10:05.070 --> 00:10:08.820
in that same way, where you're
focused on the plant itself,

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:11.138
and then you built
your meal from that.

00:10:11.138 --> 00:10:15.330
So the sea beans are out
of Spores and Succulents.

00:10:15.330 --> 00:10:18.720
And actually, I don't
see my sea beans.

00:10:18.720 --> 00:10:22.380
So maybe they're still chilling.

00:10:22.380 --> 00:10:24.540
So while the sea beans
are on their way,

00:10:24.540 --> 00:10:26.850
I'll tell you a
little bit about them.

00:10:26.850 --> 00:10:31.740
So sea beans are a
aquatic succulent.

00:10:31.740 --> 00:10:35.296
They grow in salt-water
marshes on the coastline.

00:10:35.296 --> 00:10:36.795
So one of the cool
things about them

00:10:36.795 --> 00:10:39.200
is that they're
native to this area.

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:40.260
Thank you.

00:10:40.260 --> 00:10:42.320
You can actually
go out and forage

00:10:42.320 --> 00:10:44.910
for sea beans on our coastline.

00:10:44.910 --> 00:10:49.030
And you can also grow these if
you have a pretty salty soil.

00:10:49.030 --> 00:10:51.566
But you can forage
for them, or you

00:10:51.566 --> 00:10:53.924
can go to stores like Berkeley
Bowl or farmer's markets.

00:10:53.924 --> 00:10:55.590
And I know that they
actually serve them

00:10:55.590 --> 00:10:57.435
in the Google kitchens
too, so a lot of you

00:10:57.435 --> 00:10:58.830
have probably had these.

00:10:58.830 --> 00:11:01.950
But I love to just walk
around Berkeley Bowl

00:11:01.950 --> 00:11:04.150
and kind of watch
shoppers examine things,

00:11:04.150 --> 00:11:05.900
like, oh my god, what
do you do with that?

00:11:05.900 --> 00:11:08.040
And it's kind of
a community where

00:11:08.040 --> 00:11:09.690
if you see someone
grabbing something

00:11:09.690 --> 00:11:11.090
that you don't
recognize, there's

00:11:11.090 --> 00:11:12.922
permission to ask,
like, OK, well,

00:11:12.922 --> 00:11:14.380
what are you going
to do with that?

00:11:14.380 --> 00:11:15.588
And, what does it taste like?

00:11:15.588 --> 00:11:18.060
So that's how I learned a
lot with just hanging out

00:11:18.060 --> 00:11:20.070
at the store and
kind of observing

00:11:20.070 --> 00:11:21.660
what other people were doing.

00:11:21.660 --> 00:11:24.300
But sea beans are the one
thing that, when I grab them,

00:11:24.300 --> 00:11:27.510
people are constantly asking
me what I do with them.

00:11:27.510 --> 00:11:29.980
And the reason I
love these is you

00:11:29.980 --> 00:11:32.100
really don't have to
do anything to them.

00:11:32.100 --> 00:11:34.012
Because they are
a succulent, they

00:11:34.012 --> 00:11:35.970
have that, like, nice
crispiness like you would

00:11:35.970 --> 00:11:38.440
expect from biting into, like--

00:11:38.440 --> 00:11:41.230
think of these as kind of
like miniature aloe veras.

00:11:41.230 --> 00:11:44.160
So it's filled with this
really nice, refreshing liquid

00:11:44.160 --> 00:11:47.370
that bursts with salt water
when you crunch into it.

00:11:47.370 --> 00:11:50.270
So I find it super addicting
to just snack on these

00:11:50.270 --> 00:11:51.540
by themselves.

00:11:51.540 --> 00:11:53.620
You can also throw
them onto a salad.

00:11:53.620 --> 00:11:55.205
You can stir-fry them.

00:11:55.205 --> 00:11:58.040
You don't want to cook them
too long because then they

00:11:58.040 --> 00:12:00.960
lose that crunch that
makes them so special.

00:12:00.960 --> 00:12:05.170
So in this recipe, we're doing
a sea bean and soba salad.

00:12:05.170 --> 00:12:07.950
And the reason it's my
favorite way to eat these

00:12:07.950 --> 00:12:11.610
is because soba noodles
are really silky and soft,

00:12:11.610 --> 00:12:14.860
and so it's really nice to
have them mixed with this kind

00:12:14.860 --> 00:12:20.740
of similar width item that has a
nice, different contrast to it.

00:12:20.740 --> 00:12:25.410
So to get started, we have
water boiling over here.

00:12:25.410 --> 00:12:28.470
So we're just going to
cook our soba noodles.

00:12:28.470 --> 00:12:31.970
And soba are actually--

00:12:31.970 --> 00:12:33.726
they're Japanese
buckwheat noodles.

00:12:33.726 --> 00:12:38.402
And if you have celiac disease,
or you're gluten-intolerant,

00:12:38.402 --> 00:12:40.370
buckwheat doesn't have
gluten, so they're

00:12:40.370 --> 00:12:42.355
a nice gluten-free alternative.

00:12:42.355 --> 00:12:44.900
You just have to be sure that
you check the ingredient label,

00:12:44.900 --> 00:12:47.740
because a lot of soba noodles
that you find at grocery stores

00:12:47.740 --> 00:12:49.930
are actually mixed with wheat.

00:12:49.930 --> 00:12:52.242
I'm not sure about the
ones in this kitchen,

00:12:52.242 --> 00:12:53.980
but if you're cooking
these at home,

00:12:53.980 --> 00:12:58.950
just buy a package that
says "100% buckwheat."

00:12:58.950 --> 00:13:02.710
So with soba noodles, they
can get mushy very fast,

00:13:02.710 --> 00:13:04.621
and so it's very
important-- we're just

00:13:04.621 --> 00:13:05.870
going to put these in the pot.

00:13:05.870 --> 00:13:11.470
It's very important to cook
them about a minute or two less

00:13:11.470 --> 00:13:12.880
than it says on the package.

00:13:12.880 --> 00:13:14.690
Because I find if
you go the whole way,

00:13:14.690 --> 00:13:17.310
they always cook a little
longer after you take them out,

00:13:17.310 --> 00:13:19.410
even if you run them
under cold water.

00:13:19.410 --> 00:13:22.200
And they can get
mushy very fast.

00:13:22.200 --> 00:13:25.939
So typically that's maybe
for five to seven minutes you

00:13:25.939 --> 00:13:28.026
want to cook theses.

00:13:28.026 --> 00:13:29.900
Fortunately, we don't
have to wait that long.

00:13:29.900 --> 00:13:31.850
We have some already cooked.

00:13:31.850 --> 00:13:34.350
So what I do at home
is I drain these.

00:13:34.350 --> 00:13:36.470
I run them under cold water.

00:13:36.470 --> 00:13:39.390
And that helps stop the
cooking, but also it

00:13:39.390 --> 00:13:41.390
washes off some of
that starch that-- you

00:13:41.390 --> 00:13:43.097
know when you cook
noodles and they sit,

00:13:43.097 --> 00:13:44.430
and they're in this, like, glob?

00:13:44.430 --> 00:13:45.900
So we don't want that.

00:13:45.900 --> 00:13:47.420
So you wash it off.

00:13:47.420 --> 00:13:52.355
And then I immediately
add the sesame oil.

00:13:52.355 --> 00:13:57.180
So the reason I do that is
because, one, it prevents them

00:13:57.180 --> 00:14:02.385
from sticking
together, and two, it--

00:14:02.385 --> 00:14:05.010
maybe this is in my head, but I
think it kind of creates, like,

00:14:05.010 --> 00:14:07.150
a protective coating
around the noodle

00:14:07.150 --> 00:14:10.060
so that it doesn't continue
to soak up moisture and get

00:14:10.060 --> 00:14:12.610
soggier and soggier over time.

00:14:12.610 --> 00:14:15.090
So maybe that's-- like I
said, maybe I invented that,

00:14:15.090 --> 00:14:17.590
but I think it works.

00:14:17.590 --> 00:14:20.760
So you're just going to
kind of mix those up.

00:14:20.760 --> 00:14:23.020
And then I like this
salad pretty chilled,

00:14:23.020 --> 00:14:26.320
so I put this in the
fridge for about an hour

00:14:26.320 --> 00:14:28.629
or overnight if I'm
making this ahead of time.

00:14:28.629 --> 00:14:30.170
And then I pull it
out right when I'm

00:14:30.170 --> 00:14:32.440
ready to assemble the salad.

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:35.250
So this is really easy dish.

00:14:35.250 --> 00:14:37.525
All we're going to do--
our sea beans are done.

00:14:37.525 --> 00:14:39.239
We don't have to do
anything to them.

00:14:39.239 --> 00:14:41.530
We're just going to add some
brightness and some crunch

00:14:41.530 --> 00:14:45.576
to the salad through
some green onion.

00:14:45.576 --> 00:14:47.520
So for green onions--

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:49.395
oh, they've already
removed the tops.

00:14:49.395 --> 00:14:51.270
So I don't really have
much to show you here.

00:14:51.270 --> 00:14:53.786
We're just going
to put these down.

00:14:53.786 --> 00:14:55.950
I can tell you a little
bit about knives.

00:14:55.950 --> 00:14:59.550
So use whatever knives
you're comfortable with.

00:14:59.550 --> 00:15:02.180
My favorite is this really
banged up nakiri knife.

00:15:02.180 --> 00:15:05.770
This is a knife specifically
designed for vegetables,

00:15:05.770 --> 00:15:07.330
and that's because it's--

00:15:07.330 --> 00:15:09.890
rather than a
chef's knife that's

00:15:09.890 --> 00:15:13.650
curved and is meant to be
used in a rocking motion,

00:15:13.650 --> 00:15:15.810
the nakiri knife is flat-edged.

00:15:15.810 --> 00:15:18.120
And so it's really just
an up-and-down knife.

00:15:18.120 --> 00:15:20.670
So you can kind of do that--

00:15:20.670 --> 00:15:22.687
across the cutting board
and chop really fast.

00:15:22.687 --> 00:15:25.785
And you don't end up getting
those strings of vegetables

00:15:25.785 --> 00:15:27.660
that are still attached
to each other, right?

00:15:27.660 --> 00:15:30.890
Like when you cut celery, and
then you take your knife away

00:15:30.890 --> 00:15:33.000
and you find they're
all still in a row.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.610
So I like this knife
because that doesn't happen.

00:15:35.610 --> 00:15:37.310
There are prettier
versions of this

00:15:37.310 --> 00:15:40.280
that aren't chipped and rusted,
but this is the one that I use.

00:15:40.280 --> 00:15:43.040
So we're just going to
run our knife through.

00:15:46.330 --> 00:15:50.110
And for the green
onion we use the white

00:15:50.110 --> 00:15:51.558
and the light-green parts.

00:15:55.960 --> 00:16:01.493
Has anyone ever cut themselves
on a filming of a Google food

00:16:01.493 --> 00:16:02.440
talk?

00:16:02.440 --> 00:16:04.950
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: Yeah, we
have good editing, though.

00:16:04.950 --> 00:16:07.241
LAURA MCLIVELY: That would
be a chef's darkest moments,

00:16:07.241 --> 00:16:10.480
if you, like, cut off your
finger in one of these things.

00:16:10.480 --> 00:16:12.020
So we're going to chops those.

00:16:12.020 --> 00:16:13.980
And then we are going
to use some chili.

00:16:13.980 --> 00:16:17.020
And you can use, again, whatever
peppers or chillies you like.

00:16:17.020 --> 00:16:18.520
I'm going to go
ahead and turn these

00:16:18.520 --> 00:16:20.895
off because, let's be honest,
this was just for the demo.

00:16:20.895 --> 00:16:22.754
We're not going to use those.

00:16:22.754 --> 00:16:24.670
You can use whatever
chili or pepper you like.

00:16:24.670 --> 00:16:28.650
I like Fresno chilies because
they have the same heat

00:16:28.650 --> 00:16:30.040
level, similar to a jalapeno.

00:16:30.040 --> 00:16:31.150
But they're red.

00:16:31.150 --> 00:16:32.836
So typically, when
you're cooking

00:16:32.836 --> 00:16:34.210
with a lot of
vegetables, there's

00:16:34.210 --> 00:16:35.668
a whole lot of
green in there, so I

00:16:35.668 --> 00:16:39.024
like to seek out chilies
to add some color.

00:16:39.024 --> 00:16:41.410
So the easiest way
to slice a chili

00:16:41.410 --> 00:16:46.790
is to just slice the
chili off of the seed.

00:16:46.790 --> 00:16:48.270
But then you end up with strips.

00:16:48.270 --> 00:16:50.640
So if you want julienne
it, that's fine.

00:16:50.640 --> 00:16:52.740
For this salad, we're
going to slice it

00:16:52.740 --> 00:16:55.450
in rounds just because it
looks a little prettier.

00:16:55.450 --> 00:16:59.585
So what you can do is you just
slice up until about halfway

00:16:59.585 --> 00:17:00.460
when the seeds start.

00:17:04.980 --> 00:17:11.490
And then, once you see seeds,
you can take a little melon

00:17:11.490 --> 00:17:15.970
baller or a small spoon, and--
this is my little compost

00:17:15.970 --> 00:17:16.810
pile--

00:17:16.810 --> 00:17:20.060
and just scoop out the seeds.

00:17:20.060 --> 00:17:25.369
And that way, you get rounds but
without the white pit and the--

00:17:25.369 --> 00:17:27.625
or the white membranes
and the seeds.

00:17:27.625 --> 00:17:29.365
The seeds are where
all the heat is,

00:17:29.365 --> 00:17:32.070
so if you want some
of that extra heat,

00:17:32.070 --> 00:17:35.010
you can keep a couple
and throw them in there.

00:17:35.010 --> 00:17:39.932
But I usually cut them out
so that it doesn't upset

00:17:39.932 --> 00:17:42.802
people who aren't spice lovers.

00:17:42.802 --> 00:17:44.980
So then it's pretty
fragile because you've

00:17:44.980 --> 00:17:45.980
removed the seeds.

00:17:45.980 --> 00:17:49.095
So you want to be careful if
you are using a chef's knife,

00:17:49.095 --> 00:17:52.020
that you don't just crush it
and open up the nice disc.

00:17:52.020 --> 00:17:54.250
So you just want to be
a little more careful

00:17:54.250 --> 00:17:58.400
and maybe slice so
that they stay intact.

00:18:02.900 --> 00:18:04.330
So there you go.

00:18:04.330 --> 00:18:07.400
You have your cut chili.

00:18:07.400 --> 00:18:09.860
So we're going to
actually add a cup.

00:18:09.860 --> 00:18:12.252
And they've already
pre-sliced these for me.

00:18:15.620 --> 00:18:17.900
And then they
pre-sliced my onions.

00:18:17.900 --> 00:18:20.100
Just [INAUDIBLE] things.

00:18:20.100 --> 00:18:22.370
And then they pre-sliced
my Thai chili.

00:18:22.370 --> 00:18:24.480
So I love-- sorry,
not Thai chili.

00:18:24.480 --> 00:18:25.270
Thai basil.

00:18:25.270 --> 00:18:26.520
I love all kinds of basil.

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:29.150
And in my garden, sometimes
this one looks funky,

00:18:29.150 --> 00:18:30.409
and I use the regular basil.

00:18:30.409 --> 00:18:31.450
It doesn't really matter.

00:18:31.450 --> 00:18:33.320
But if you're trying
to keep this kind

00:18:33.320 --> 00:18:39.660
of a Southeast Asian dish, you
could go with the Thai basil.

00:18:39.660 --> 00:18:42.430
And then while this
is kind of sitting

00:18:42.430 --> 00:18:45.820
over there doing nothing, we
want to toast our sesame seeds.

00:18:45.820 --> 00:18:49.910
So I usually use
black sesame seeds.

00:18:49.910 --> 00:18:50.963
How do I turn this on?

00:18:50.963 --> 00:18:51.838
SPEAKER: [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:51.838 --> 00:18:53.525
LAURA MCLIVELY: Hold it down.

00:18:53.525 --> 00:18:55.093
SPEAKER: And now go ahead and--

00:18:55.093 --> 00:18:56.176
LAURA MCLIVELY: Go up, OK.

00:18:59.560 --> 00:19:03.730
So I like using the black
sesame seeds because they just

00:19:03.730 --> 00:19:05.830
provide such a nice contrast.

00:19:05.830 --> 00:19:07.287
You can see them
better on dishes.

00:19:07.287 --> 00:19:09.472
Did I do that right?

00:19:09.472 --> 00:19:12.467
Oh, I'm using the wrong burner.

00:19:12.467 --> 00:19:14.034
SPEAKER: That's
actually a timer.

00:19:14.034 --> 00:19:16.450
LAURA MCLIVELY: That's what
was beeping over there.

00:19:16.450 --> 00:19:18.700
I was like, why is this
pan not getting hot?

00:19:18.700 --> 00:19:19.980
SPEAKER: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:19:19.980 --> 00:19:21.573
LAURA MCLIVELY: Yes, thank you.

00:19:21.573 --> 00:19:23.950
Black sesame seeds
just look so pretty.

00:19:23.950 --> 00:19:26.090
And again, I think it's
one of those things that

00:19:26.090 --> 00:19:27.710
are underutilized in kitchens.

00:19:27.710 --> 00:19:31.320
Oftentime, you see sesame
seeds on breads or pastries

00:19:31.320 --> 00:19:33.900
and on salads, and it's
always the golden ones.

00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:36.730
And so once again, just even
if you just go to the store

00:19:36.730 --> 00:19:39.299
and pick out a different
spice or something

00:19:39.299 --> 00:19:40.840
different from the
bulk bins, I think

00:19:40.840 --> 00:19:43.050
you end up realizing
how versatile it is

00:19:43.050 --> 00:19:44.297
and how much fun you'd have.

00:19:44.297 --> 00:19:47.110
One of the things I'd love
to do with black sesame seeds

00:19:47.110 --> 00:19:48.450
is to make tahini.

00:19:48.450 --> 00:19:50.430
So we've all seen
tahini, and it's

00:19:50.430 --> 00:19:52.475
kind of peanut-butter looking.

00:19:52.475 --> 00:19:54.600
My husband is definitely
allergic to peanut butter,

00:19:54.600 --> 00:19:57.179
so I tend to keep things
away from the house that

00:19:57.179 --> 00:19:59.470
even remotely look like it
because he's just like, ugh,

00:19:59.470 --> 00:20:01.640
what is that?

00:20:01.640 --> 00:20:04.320
So usually I buy
black sesame seeds,

00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:05.650
and I make that into a tahini.

00:20:05.650 --> 00:20:08.860
And it's really
glossy and beautiful.

00:20:08.860 --> 00:20:12.320
And in fact, it's in one of
the recipes for treviso spring

00:20:12.320 --> 00:20:12.820
rolls.

00:20:12.820 --> 00:20:14.960
So kind of like a
Vietnamese-style fresh spring

00:20:14.960 --> 00:20:15.460
roll.

00:20:15.460 --> 00:20:18.390
And you dip it in the
black tahini afterwards.

00:20:18.390 --> 00:20:21.290
Which, I see treviso out
there in your kitchen,

00:20:21.290 --> 00:20:23.880
so I'm glad to see some of
the items in this cookbook

00:20:23.880 --> 00:20:25.945
out there.

00:20:25.945 --> 00:20:27.570
So to test the sesame
seeds, we're just

00:20:27.570 --> 00:20:30.171
going to add them to the pan.

00:20:30.171 --> 00:20:33.070
And this takes about a
minute or two for them

00:20:33.070 --> 00:20:36.070
to start to smell fragrant.

00:20:36.070 --> 00:20:37.570
You don't want them
to burn, so just

00:20:37.570 --> 00:20:39.640
kind of shake your pan
every once in a while,

00:20:39.640 --> 00:20:41.620
and make sure that
they're moving around.

00:20:41.620 --> 00:20:44.220
And when they smell [INAUDIBLE],,
take them off and let

00:20:44.220 --> 00:20:47.760
them cool so that they don't
continue to cook in the pan.

00:20:47.760 --> 00:20:51.630
Because there's nothing worse
than burned seeds and nuts,

00:20:51.630 --> 00:20:53.330
right?

00:20:53.330 --> 00:20:55.552
So give those a little shake.

00:20:58.510 --> 00:21:00.745
And then we're just going
to make our dressing.

00:21:00.745 --> 00:21:06.879
So for our dressing, we
have some minced ginger.

00:21:06.879 --> 00:21:08.745
I'm being a messy cook.

00:21:08.745 --> 00:21:10.786
Let me move these
out of the way.

00:21:10.786 --> 00:21:17.860
We're going to do some fresh,
minced ginger, some soy sauce.

00:21:17.860 --> 00:21:20.500
And again, if you're keeping
this recipe gluten-free

00:21:20.500 --> 00:21:23.410
by buying 100%
buckwheat noodles,

00:21:23.410 --> 00:21:25.420
you could also
use tamari instead

00:21:25.420 --> 00:21:28.936
because that's the gluten-free
alternative to soy sauce.

00:21:28.936 --> 00:21:34.360
So lime juice and our honey.

00:21:34.360 --> 00:21:36.550
So typically in
Southeast Asian cooking,

00:21:36.550 --> 00:21:40.420
you're aiming for a nice balance
between salt, acid, and sweet.

00:21:40.420 --> 00:21:43.120
Or really in all
cooking, really.

00:21:43.120 --> 00:21:45.620
But particularly in
Southeast Asian cooking,

00:21:45.620 --> 00:21:47.970
you want a little bit
of sweetness and lots

00:21:47.970 --> 00:21:50.670
of acid and some
salt. And so that's

00:21:50.670 --> 00:21:53.460
why we're adding the honey,
is for that sweetness.

00:21:53.460 --> 00:22:00.640
And last but not least,
our rice vinegar.

00:22:00.640 --> 00:22:05.905
And actually, I hear my
little sesame seeds popping.

00:22:05.905 --> 00:22:06.871
Yep.

00:22:06.871 --> 00:22:08.954
So you just want to kind
of stick your nose in it,

00:22:08.954 --> 00:22:14.110
and when it smells
done, it's done.

00:22:14.110 --> 00:22:15.102
OK.

00:22:15.102 --> 00:22:19.566
So we're just going
to whisk this up.

00:22:19.566 --> 00:22:21.054
And dump it on.

00:22:27.998 --> 00:22:30.570
And last but not least, we're
going to add our sea beans.

00:22:30.570 --> 00:22:32.140
So, like I said,
you don't really

00:22:32.140 --> 00:22:33.450
have to do anything to these.

00:22:33.450 --> 00:22:35.400
They're best
chilled, because they

00:22:35.400 --> 00:22:40.575
can get kind of, like, limp
if they're out too long.

00:22:40.575 --> 00:22:43.500
And really, you can just
put them in as they are,

00:22:43.500 --> 00:22:45.350
but if you have some
that are really long--

00:22:45.350 --> 00:22:47.420
these are actually pretty tiny.

00:22:47.420 --> 00:22:48.597
But some of these are long.

00:22:48.597 --> 00:22:50.180
And so let's say
you're having someone

00:22:50.180 --> 00:22:53.290
over, like your special friend,
and you're cooking for them.

00:22:53.290 --> 00:22:55.400
You don't want mouthfuls
of succulent tentacles

00:22:55.400 --> 00:22:56.640
falling out of your mouth.

00:22:56.640 --> 00:23:00.140
So you can put them
on your cutting board,

00:23:00.140 --> 00:23:01.960
and maybe run a knife
through it once.

00:23:01.960 --> 00:23:03.501
You don't want to
chop them up a lot,

00:23:03.501 --> 00:23:05.440
but just kind of do one
in half so that there

00:23:05.440 --> 00:23:09.274
are more bite-sized pieces.

00:23:09.274 --> 00:23:10.355
So we'll just add this.

00:23:10.355 --> 00:23:14.760
And this bowl is going to
be really hard to toss in.

00:23:14.760 --> 00:23:17.770
