00:26:13.762 --> 00:26:17.300
So our last recipe we're
going to demonstrate

00:26:17.300 --> 00:26:20.990
is lemongrass coconut ice cream.

00:26:20.990 --> 00:26:24.823
So I realize that most of you
have had lemongrass by now.

00:26:24.823 --> 00:26:28.760
It's not so much an
obscure ingredient.

00:26:28.760 --> 00:26:33.760
But I still think
that I've met--

00:26:33.760 --> 00:26:38.120
a lot of my friends and a lot
of fellow cooks I know still

00:26:38.120 --> 00:26:39.460
haven't worked with it.

00:26:39.460 --> 00:26:41.340
It's like we have it
in Southeast Asian

00:26:41.340 --> 00:26:44.300
cooking when we go to a Thai
restaurant, but a lot of people

00:26:44.300 --> 00:26:46.490
haven't actually
prepared it at home.

00:26:46.490 --> 00:26:48.549
So once again, it's
like making these things

00:26:48.549 --> 00:26:50.465
kind of familiar parts
of our everyday cooking

00:26:50.465 --> 00:26:54.500
can really add some variety and
fun and a sense of discovery

00:26:54.500 --> 00:26:55.380
in the kitchen.

00:26:55.380 --> 00:26:57.150
At least that's
what it did for me.

00:26:57.150 --> 00:27:00.880
So coconut-based ice cream
is my favorite, because--

00:27:00.880 --> 00:27:04.360
I do eat regular ice cream
too, but the cool thing

00:27:04.360 --> 00:27:06.955
about coconut ice
cream is you can--

00:27:06.955 --> 00:27:09.650
something's beeping
again, the timer-- you

00:27:09.650 --> 00:27:10.955
can have it a moment's notice.

00:27:10.955 --> 00:27:12.330
Rarely do I keep
large quantities

00:27:12.330 --> 00:27:14.990
of cream just sitting
in my refrigerator,

00:27:14.990 --> 00:27:18.380
but I always have a can or two
of coconut milk in my cabinet.

00:27:18.380 --> 00:27:20.830
And so you can have ice
cream instantaneously.

00:27:20.830 --> 00:27:22.660
All you need is an
ice-cream maker.

00:27:22.660 --> 00:27:26.280
So usually the
coconut-based ice cream,

00:27:26.280 --> 00:27:28.190
you just want to add
something to flavor it.

00:27:28.190 --> 00:27:34.470
And I love lemongrass because
it has that really nice zingy,

00:27:34.470 --> 00:27:35.650
citrus-y taste.

00:27:35.650 --> 00:27:37.575
Like it actually kind
of zings in your mouth.

00:27:37.575 --> 00:27:40.005
And even a hint of pepperiness,
sort of like ginger.

00:27:40.005 --> 00:27:45.000
And so it's a nice way to cut
the richness of pure coconut

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:48.040
milk that has a
high fat content.

00:27:48.040 --> 00:27:51.425
You do want to use real regular
coconut milk, not light,

00:27:51.425 --> 00:27:53.980
so that you get a
nice creamy ice cream.

00:27:53.980 --> 00:27:56.620
So all we're going to do
is prepare lemongrass.

00:27:56.620 --> 00:27:58.850
I hope you're seeing how
easy these recipes are.

00:27:58.850 --> 00:28:00.365
It is very approachable.

00:28:00.365 --> 00:28:02.140
So things that might
look intimidating

00:28:02.140 --> 00:28:05.420
are actually quite easy
once you get used to them.

00:28:05.420 --> 00:28:09.330
So what we're going to do is
just slice off our root tip.

00:28:12.330 --> 00:28:15.640
And then I like to bruise
them sort of like you would

00:28:15.640 --> 00:28:17.970
garlic to release the layers.

00:28:17.970 --> 00:28:20.370
And also it helps break
down the cell walls

00:28:20.370 --> 00:28:25.116
and get that lemongrass
oil infusing and releasing

00:28:25.116 --> 00:28:26.710
from the layer.

00:28:26.710 --> 00:28:27.774
So you could just take--

00:28:27.774 --> 00:28:29.940
I don't want to use my
really fragile nakiri knife--

00:28:29.940 --> 00:28:33.690
you can take a chef's knife
and just kind of whack it

00:28:33.690 --> 00:28:37.340
with your hand along the stalk.

00:28:37.340 --> 00:28:39.540
And then we're just
going to slice it.

00:28:39.540 --> 00:28:40.850
It doesn't have be precise.

00:28:40.850 --> 00:28:45.000
This is just to create
some surface area

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:46.402
for the coconut milk.

00:28:50.650 --> 00:28:53.520
This is basically a two or
three-ingredient ice cream,

00:28:53.520 --> 00:28:56.520
depending on whether or
not you want to add ginger.

00:28:56.520 --> 00:29:00.195
So it's kind of as
simple as making vanilla.

00:29:00.195 --> 00:29:02.480
So you can use as much
of it as you want.

00:29:02.480 --> 00:29:07.160
I kind of stop once I get up to
the part where it branches off.

00:29:07.160 --> 00:29:12.906
And then we're going
to repeat that.

00:29:12.906 --> 00:29:16.793
If there's some layers
that look kind of--

00:29:16.793 --> 00:29:18.660
you know how onion
or celery or fennel

00:29:18.660 --> 00:29:20.719
have some of those outer,
brownish layers that

00:29:20.719 --> 00:29:22.260
look like they've
touched everything?

00:29:22.260 --> 00:29:24.510
You can remove an
outer layer like that,

00:29:24.510 --> 00:29:27.114
and then do your bruising.

00:29:27.114 --> 00:29:28.530
This one looks fine.

00:29:33.730 --> 00:29:36.430
If you have delicate hands,
you can use, like, a--

00:29:36.430 --> 00:29:39.250
my mom has a wooden mortar
and pestle on her counter.

00:29:39.250 --> 00:29:42.140
And she always just
took the actual mortar

00:29:42.140 --> 00:29:44.368
and banged it on her
garlic or whatever.

00:29:59.038 --> 00:30:00.510
And here's our last stalk.

00:30:00.510 --> 00:30:05.910
I used three because I
like it quite lemony.

00:30:05.910 --> 00:30:08.860
And also, this is growing
in the Google garden.

00:30:08.860 --> 00:30:11.980
So you guys are growing
a lot of these things.

00:30:11.980 --> 00:30:16.410
I have this growing at home, but
mine is kind of spindly still.

00:30:16.410 --> 00:30:18.084
It's not big enough.

00:30:21.006 --> 00:30:22.960
OK.

00:30:22.960 --> 00:30:26.929
So making this ice cream
is as simple as putting

00:30:26.929 --> 00:30:28.201
this in a pot.

00:30:32.020 --> 00:30:36.640
And you're going to
add your coconut milk.

00:30:36.640 --> 00:30:38.820
They have these huge
industrial-sized cans

00:30:38.820 --> 00:30:42.295
of coconut milk in this kitchen,
so that's why it's pre-poured.

00:30:42.295 --> 00:30:45.308
But at home, this would
be about two cans.

00:30:48.182 --> 00:30:51.850
So we've got our coconut
milk and our sugar.

00:30:55.130 --> 00:30:59.110
And like I said, if you'd
like, you can add some ginger.

00:30:59.110 --> 00:31:03.400
I just add a couple
coins, three or four.

00:31:07.540 --> 00:31:09.050
And you just heat it.

00:31:09.050 --> 00:31:14.818
So you put this on your stove,
if I can work this burner.

00:31:14.818 --> 00:31:18.290
This one, on.

00:31:18.290 --> 00:31:20.640
And the goal is just
to get it to the point

00:31:20.640 --> 00:31:22.383
where it's simmering,
because since this

00:31:22.383 --> 00:31:25.240
is sort of an infusion,
you're really just wanting

00:31:25.240 --> 00:31:26.810
to treat it like a tea.

00:31:26.810 --> 00:31:29.600
So get the coconut
milk to simmer,

00:31:29.600 --> 00:31:33.480
and then you can turn
it off and let it sit.

00:31:33.480 --> 00:31:36.876
So what I do is I,
once it's simmering,

00:31:36.876 --> 00:31:39.830
I let it sit for about
15 minutes in the pot

00:31:39.830 --> 00:31:42.140
that I'm simmering
it in so that it's

00:31:42.140 --> 00:31:44.850
infusing at its maximum heat.

00:31:44.850 --> 00:31:48.520
And then you take this mixture,
and you want to chill it.

00:31:48.520 --> 00:31:50.810
Because when you're
making ice cream,

00:31:50.810 --> 00:31:52.730
it's really important
that the solution

00:31:52.730 --> 00:31:54.479
that you're putting
in the ice-cream maker

00:31:54.479 --> 00:31:56.210
is as cold as possible.

00:31:56.210 --> 00:31:58.900
Because if it takes
too long to freeze,

00:31:58.900 --> 00:32:00.860
you end up getting ice crystals.

00:32:00.860 --> 00:32:05.120
So I usually will kind of
make this up the night before

00:32:05.120 --> 00:32:06.540
and keep it in my fridge.

00:32:06.540 --> 00:32:09.350
And then when we're
sitting down for dinner,

00:32:09.350 --> 00:32:10.910
I throw this in my
ice-cream maker.

00:32:10.910 --> 00:32:12.670
It takes about 15 to
20 minutes to freeze,

00:32:12.670 --> 00:32:15.240
and it's done by the time
we finish our dinner.

00:32:15.240 --> 00:32:16.606
I feel there's nothing--

00:32:16.606 --> 00:32:20.010
it's a really nice touch
to serve homemade ice cream

00:32:20.010 --> 00:32:21.950
when you're having people over.

00:32:21.950 --> 00:32:23.690
And they think it's
like this big deal,

00:32:23.690 --> 00:32:25.940
but it's really super simple.

00:32:25.940 --> 00:32:27.940
And so it's a nice way
to serve people something

00:32:27.940 --> 00:32:30.630
that seems special but that
doesn't take a lot of time.

00:32:30.630 --> 00:32:34.430
So I don't think we'll we
for this to actually simmer,

00:32:34.430 --> 00:32:38.810
but let's just pretend it's
simmered, we've chilled it.

00:32:38.810 --> 00:32:42.020
And if you want to chill
it fast, not in your fridge

00:32:42.020 --> 00:32:44.075
overnight, you could
just set up a ice bath.

00:32:44.075 --> 00:32:47.430
So put a bowl in a
larger bowl of ice

00:32:47.430 --> 00:32:49.690
and kind of let it
sit there and stir it.

00:32:49.690 --> 00:32:52.210
That will take maybe 30
minutes to get it to the point

00:32:52.210 --> 00:32:53.730
where it's really chilled.

00:32:53.730 --> 00:32:56.370
And then-- I don't think I
have an ice-cream maker here,

00:32:56.370 --> 00:32:57.203
but they've used it.

00:32:57.203 --> 00:32:59.530
But you would turn on
your ice-cream maker.

00:32:59.530 --> 00:33:02.590
And in the interest of not
dirtying extra equipment,

00:33:02.590 --> 00:33:05.940
I just hold a strainer,
a fine-mesh strainer,

00:33:05.940 --> 00:33:08.660
over the ice-cream maker,
and I dump it directly in.

00:33:08.660 --> 00:33:10.910
And it keeps out the solids.

00:33:10.910 --> 00:33:13.380
So we basically want to leave
the lemongrass and ginger

00:33:13.380 --> 00:33:18.470
in there as long as possible so
that it's infusing to the max.

00:33:18.470 --> 00:33:20.530
So that's it for
