but just going back
to the Berkeley

00:35:29.090 --> 00:35:31.440
Bowl-- who has not been to
the Berkeley Bowl before?

00:35:33.950 --> 00:35:35.290
And I'm not singling anyone out.

00:35:35.290 --> 00:35:36.581
You can't see on camera anyway.

00:35:36.581 --> 00:35:38.690
But there's some cool
fun facts about the Bowl.

00:35:38.690 --> 00:35:40.260
So it used to be
a bowling alley.

00:35:40.260 --> 00:35:43.480
It's owned by a husband and
wife, and now their son.

00:35:43.480 --> 00:35:46.079
They've owned it
for several decades.

00:35:46.079 --> 00:35:47.370
There's two locations, correct?

00:35:47.370 --> 00:35:48.097
LAURA MCLIVELY: Mm-hmm.

00:35:48.097 --> 00:35:49.260
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: And you
said there was over, what,

00:35:49.260 --> 00:35:51.840
1,000-plus different
ingredients in there?

00:35:51.840 --> 00:35:52.743
LAURA MCLIVELY: Yes.

00:35:52.743 --> 00:35:56.460
So for those who haven't been,
the reason this store can

00:35:56.460 --> 00:35:58.174
inspire a whole cookbook--

00:35:58.174 --> 00:35:59.590
I don't work for
them, by the way.

00:35:59.590 --> 00:36:01.120
A lot of people think I do.

00:36:01.120 --> 00:36:04.000
I'm just a shopper who
was inspired by the store.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:07.530
And it's because
it's hard to find

00:36:07.530 --> 00:36:12.080
another place that has so many
produce items under one roof.

00:36:12.080 --> 00:36:13.945
This book is usable
even if you don't

00:36:13.945 --> 00:36:15.570
live next to Berkeley
Bowl because it's

00:36:15.570 --> 00:36:18.060
kind of like a fun
treasure map to go find

00:36:18.060 --> 00:36:20.740
these things at a
certain farmer's market,

00:36:20.740 --> 00:36:24.240
and then maybe you go find
nopales at the Hispanic market.

00:36:24.240 --> 00:36:27.390
And then you can find burdock
root at the Asian market.

00:36:27.390 --> 00:36:29.620
But you'd have to go to a
lot of different places.

00:36:29.620 --> 00:36:31.706
And that's fun in its own right.

00:36:31.706 --> 00:36:33.300
But the cool thing
about Berkeley Bowl

00:36:33.300 --> 00:36:35.910
is all those things
are under one roof.

00:36:35.910 --> 00:36:41.370
And that's because Glenn
Yasuda, the original owner,

00:36:41.370 --> 00:36:42.520
his family were farmers.

00:36:42.520 --> 00:36:47.220
And Diane, his wife, her family
owned another produce shop

00:36:47.220 --> 00:36:48.270
in Berkeley.

00:36:48.270 --> 00:36:51.970
And they really had this
dream of opening a produce

00:36:51.970 --> 00:36:54.210
store in front of the
house where they lived,

00:36:54.210 --> 00:36:55.740
sort of like things
are in Japan.

00:36:55.740 --> 00:36:57.805
And so they bought
this bowling alley

00:36:57.805 --> 00:36:59.180
that was in front
of their house,

00:36:59.180 --> 00:37:00.810
and they turned it
into a produce shop.

00:37:00.810 --> 00:37:02.940
So originally, it
was just produce.

00:37:02.940 --> 00:37:06.120
And he has always had
this commitment to,

00:37:06.120 --> 00:37:08.090
if I can find it,
I will provide it.

00:37:08.090 --> 00:37:10.760
And knowing that he
has this store in one

00:37:10.760 --> 00:37:13.945
of the most culturally
diverse areas in the country,

00:37:13.945 --> 00:37:18.710
with over 112 languages
spoken in the Bay Area,

00:37:18.710 --> 00:37:22.430
he kind of knew, well, if I
can find this niche item, if I

00:37:22.430 --> 00:37:24.640
can find taro
leaf, there will be

00:37:24.640 --> 00:37:26.742
someone that is
excited to see taro

00:37:26.742 --> 00:37:28.350
leaf at their local market.

00:37:28.350 --> 00:37:29.620
And he was right.

00:37:29.620 --> 00:37:31.272
He kept finding
these niche items

00:37:31.272 --> 00:37:33.210
and providing more
and more and more.

00:37:33.210 --> 00:37:34.800
And more and more
people came, knowing

00:37:34.800 --> 00:37:36.480
that they could
find the foods that

00:37:36.480 --> 00:37:39.950
maybe were from their cultural
background, all in one spot.

00:37:39.950 --> 00:37:45.410
By the way, this is simmering,
so we're going to turn it off.

00:37:45.410 --> 00:37:48.230
So when I first set
foot in Berkeley Bowl,

00:37:48.230 --> 00:37:50.040
I saw things like this.

00:37:53.620 --> 00:37:56.020
And granted, this
is a room with a lot

00:37:56.020 --> 00:37:57.770
of people from maybe
different backgrounds

00:37:57.770 --> 00:38:00.290
as well, so some of these
things might be normal to you.

00:38:00.290 --> 00:38:03.800
Like Scott was saying
his wife is Fijian.

00:38:03.800 --> 00:38:10.340
And so she grew up eating
Indian bitter melon.

00:38:10.340 --> 00:38:13.094
But maybe she didn't grow
up eating salad savoy.

00:38:13.094 --> 00:38:15.510
And so it's kind of cool because
you can go to this store,

00:38:15.510 --> 00:38:17.280
and you're always
going to find something

00:38:17.280 --> 00:38:18.890
that you don't recognize.

00:38:18.890 --> 00:38:22.412
But when I walked in, I saw
these things, like this--

00:38:22.412 --> 00:38:26.080
this one's kind of a small one,
but these can get up to, like,

00:38:26.080 --> 00:38:27.200
3 or 4 feet, this root.

00:38:27.200 --> 00:38:29.241
And I'm picking it up,
like, what I do with this?

00:38:29.241 --> 00:38:32.250
Like, oh, my god,
this is so cool!

00:38:32.250 --> 00:38:34.734
And so again, I kind of would
ask people that were also

00:38:34.734 --> 00:38:35.900
picking it up, what is this?

00:38:35.900 --> 00:38:37.169
What does it taste like?

00:38:37.169 --> 00:38:38.960
And then ultimately
kind of got the courage

00:38:38.960 --> 00:38:42.000
to bring these home
and experiment.

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:43.923
So usually I'd bring
it home, and I'd

00:38:43.923 --> 00:38:45.340
try it a couple
of different ways.

00:38:45.340 --> 00:38:49.740
Like, I'd grate it, I'd cook
it, I'd braise it, I'd roast it.

00:38:49.740 --> 00:38:52.270
And then I'd see what
way I liked the best.

00:38:52.270 --> 00:38:54.933
And I tried to do that
before looking it up,

00:38:54.933 --> 00:39:00.110
because it's really easy to kind
of pigeon hole an ingredient

00:39:00.110 --> 00:39:03.050
into a certain context, like,
oh, this has to be prepared--

00:39:03.050 --> 00:39:05.089
like this is typically--

00:39:05.089 --> 00:39:07.130
well, it's used a lot of
different ways in Japan,

00:39:07.130 --> 00:39:13.400
but oftentimes it's grated and
simmered in a sweet solution,

00:39:13.400 --> 00:39:15.241
and it's used as a
topping on things.

00:39:15.241 --> 00:39:17.240
So it's like, well, I
don't want to repeat that,

00:39:17.240 --> 00:39:21.810
so I try to play with these
things before looking them up

00:39:21.810 --> 00:39:26.380
and come up with my own ways
and my own family dishes

00:39:26.380 --> 00:39:28.420
to incorporate them into.

00:39:28.420 --> 00:39:30.820
So there's a lot of Spanish
and Greek dishes in this book

00:39:30.820 --> 00:39:32.450
because that was my background.

00:39:32.450 --> 00:39:35.120
And then also a
lot of dishes that

00:39:35.120 --> 00:39:38.195
were inspired by travels,
and just living in Berkeley

00:39:38.195 --> 00:39:39.842
and eating out.

00:39:39.842 --> 00:39:42.050
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: So before
the food comes to you--

00:39:42.050 --> 00:39:44.240
and they're plating it up now-
are there additional questions?

00:39:44.240 --> 00:39:46.406
Anyone have anything they
want to ask at this point?

00:39:46.406 --> 00:39:49.840
Because I will keep
talking, if not.

00:39:49.840 --> 00:39:50.755
Yes?

00:39:50.755 --> 00:39:53.230
AUDIENCE: Do you have
a go-to blog or site

00:39:53.230 --> 00:39:57.190
or anything that tells you
kind of how to pick produce?

00:39:57.190 --> 00:39:59.775
Because it's cool to see a
bunch of different options,

00:39:59.775 --> 00:40:01.650
but I have no idea how
to pick the right one.

00:40:01.650 --> 00:40:03.858
LAURA MCLIVELY: Yeah, that's
a really great question.

00:40:03.858 --> 00:40:05.790
So she asked if I
have a go-to resource

00:40:05.790 --> 00:40:11.616
for learning how to select
and work with produce, right?

00:40:11.616 --> 00:40:13.490
Well, first of all, I
forgot to mention that,

00:40:13.490 --> 00:40:15.340
so I'm glad you brought that up.

00:40:15.340 --> 00:40:18.964
To take the mystery away,
I-- for every item that's

00:40:18.964 --> 00:40:20.630
featured in the book,
there's a sidebar,

00:40:20.630 --> 00:40:25.280
and it has how to select
it, how to store it,

00:40:25.280 --> 00:40:27.320
when it's available,
and substitutions.

00:40:27.320 --> 00:40:30.840
Because not only-- like, if
you were living in an area

00:40:30.840 --> 00:40:33.360
where you just could
not find salad savoy,

00:40:33.360 --> 00:40:36.990
I want to make sure that you
can make the dish nonetheless.

00:40:36.990 --> 00:40:40.041
But also because you might fall
in love with a recipe, and then

00:40:40.041 --> 00:40:41.540
the item only has
a two-week season.

00:40:41.540 --> 00:40:44.340
So for instance, there's
a fiddlehead tempura

00:40:44.340 --> 00:40:47.890
in here with sriracha
creme fraiche that I love.

00:40:47.890 --> 00:40:49.892
But fiddleheads are
only around for a couple

00:40:49.892 --> 00:40:50.850
of weeks in the spring.

00:40:50.850 --> 00:40:52.260
So you can make that--

00:40:52.260 --> 00:40:54.700
I recommend using
asparagus or green beans.

00:40:54.700 --> 00:40:56.440
So I always list substitutions.

00:40:56.440 --> 00:40:59.170
But in regards to your
question about resources,

00:40:59.170 --> 00:41:01.060
one of the sites I
found really helpful

00:41:01.060 --> 00:41:03.110
is called "Specialty Produce."

00:41:03.110 --> 00:41:07.820
They have a really great website
that has everything on there.

00:41:07.820 --> 00:41:09.550
You can type it in,
and it will tell

00:41:09.550 --> 00:41:13.800
you its ethnographic
information, how to select,

00:41:13.800 --> 00:41:15.130
how to store.

00:41:15.130 --> 00:41:18.461
And then also what's cool is
they say recent sightings.

00:41:18.461 --> 00:41:20.460
So, like, "recent salad
savoy sightings," and it

00:41:20.460 --> 00:41:23.376
lists restaurants where
these things have recently

00:41:23.376 --> 00:41:24.500
been featured on the menus.

00:41:24.500 --> 00:41:26.725
So I really love that
because then I think, oh, I

00:41:26.725 --> 00:41:30.880
want to go see what they did
with Indian bitter melon,

00:41:30.880 --> 00:41:32.970
or I want to see
what they did with--

00:41:32.970 --> 00:41:35.860
what are some-- oh,
like lotus root.

00:41:35.860 --> 00:41:37.800
That's one of the more
beautiful vegetables

00:41:37.800 --> 00:41:41.490
that you can find that looks
like lace when you cut it open.

00:41:41.490 --> 00:41:45.640
So yeah, I think
specialty produce.

00:41:45.640 --> 00:41:48.160
And then the other site that
's really helpful is "Food 52."

00:41:48.160 --> 00:41:50.470
Has anyone--- yeah, [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:50.470 --> 00:41:52.810
So that's a really great
website that really goes

00:41:52.810 --> 00:41:55.400
into depth on each ingredient.

00:41:55.400 --> 00:42:00.945
And I think they
have recipes as well

00:42:00.945 --> 00:42:03.570
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: So when you
started to write this cookbook,

00:42:03.570 --> 00:42:05.280
is it what you
thought it would be as

00:42:05.280 --> 00:42:06.675
far as the investment of time?

00:42:06.675 --> 00:42:09.270
Were there any surprises
along the way on the journey?

00:42:09.270 --> 00:42:12.900
Anything you would
do differently?

00:42:12.900 --> 00:42:16.020
LAURA MCLIVELY: I should
say, so a lot of the recipes

00:42:16.020 --> 00:42:19.030
ended up coming from my blog,
and that was just for fun.

00:42:19.030 --> 00:42:20.950
You guys all work
at Google, so you'll

00:42:20.950 --> 00:42:22.950
think this is pathetic,
but, like, I didn't even

00:42:22.950 --> 00:42:25.770
know that you could tag blog
posts to make them searchable.

00:42:25.770 --> 00:42:27.170
I wasn't doing any of that.

00:42:27.170 --> 00:42:29.370
I just was doing it for fun.

00:42:29.370 --> 00:42:32.000
And so at that time, I
wasn't thinking of it

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:35.670
as a time investment,
because it was just for me.

00:42:35.670 --> 00:42:38.610
But then once I signed
the cookbook contract,

00:42:38.610 --> 00:42:41.250
I was surprised, actually.

00:42:41.250 --> 00:42:43.865
It's like coming
up with 100 recipes

00:42:43.865 --> 00:42:47.250
maybe doesn't sound
crazy, but I was doing it

00:42:47.250 --> 00:42:50.140
while still working full
time as a clinical dietitian.

00:42:50.140 --> 00:42:55.150
And so that meant I spent pretty
much every evening after work

00:42:55.150 --> 00:42:58.289
just standing in the
aisles of Berkeley Bowl.

00:42:58.289 --> 00:43:00.580
Because you never know what
you're going to find there.

00:43:00.580 --> 00:43:04.020
And so it was really hard to
develop some of these recipes

00:43:04.020 --> 00:43:08.177
because I'd find sour plums,
for instance, and go, cool!

00:43:08.177 --> 00:43:09.760
I haven't seen these
in the store yet!

00:43:09.760 --> 00:43:12.160
And I'd take them home,
I'd come up with a recipe,

00:43:12.160 --> 00:43:15.036
and then I'd go back
to get them to test it

00:43:15.036 --> 00:43:17.285
and they'd be gone already,
because these things have,

00:43:17.285 --> 00:43:18.576
like, a one or two-week season.

00:43:18.576 --> 00:43:22.770
So that made it challenging
and kind of delayed

00:43:22.770 --> 00:43:25.025
some of these recipes
coming to fruition,

00:43:25.025 --> 00:43:26.820
because I had to wait
for the next season

00:43:26.820 --> 00:43:29.405
when these things
were back available.

00:43:29.405 --> 00:43:31.590
And actually, a
little anecdote is

00:43:31.590 --> 00:43:33.600
that testing was
also a challenge

00:43:33.600 --> 00:43:37.540
because we wanted to make
sure every recipe in the book

00:43:37.540 --> 00:43:39.440
was tested at least three times.

00:43:39.440 --> 00:43:42.700
And so something to has a
really short season, again,

00:43:42.700 --> 00:43:47.100
by the time I developed a recipe
and the editor approved it,

00:43:47.100 --> 00:43:48.290
the item was gone.

00:43:48.290 --> 00:43:51.900
And so I actually had some of my
friends living in New Zealand,

00:43:51.900 --> 00:43:53.557
they became recipe testers.

00:43:53.557 --> 00:43:55.640
So it was great because
they had opposite seasons.

00:43:55.640 --> 00:43:59.000
So they had, like, a
six-month lag where I'd say,

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:03.050
OK, this one's ready, let
the New Zealand folks test it

00:44:03.050 --> 00:44:06.014
because they'll be able
to find it in six months.

00:44:06.014 --> 00:44:07.180
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: Awesome.

00:44:07.180 --> 00:44:07.910
Yes, in the back?

00:44:07.910 --> 00:44:10.555
AUDIENCE: Is there a Berkeley
Bowl equivalent in New Zealand?

00:44:10.555 --> 00:44:12.680
LAURA MCLIVELY: Is there
a Berkeley Bowl equivalent

00:44:12.680 --> 00:44:13.410
in New Zealand?

00:44:13.410 --> 00:44:16.870
It's called, like, large
sprawls of land where people

00:44:16.870 --> 00:44:18.752
can grow their own veggies.

00:44:18.752 --> 00:44:21.910
So no, I don't think
there's an actual--

00:44:21.910 --> 00:44:25.730
I don't think there's a Berkeley
Bowl equivalent anywhere.

00:44:25.730 --> 00:44:28.940
There are some really great
produce markets all around,

00:44:28.940 --> 00:44:29.690
including LA.

00:44:29.690 --> 00:44:31.870
But Berkeley Bowl
really is unique.

00:44:31.870 --> 00:44:33.800
So for those who
haven't been, please

00:44:33.800 --> 00:44:36.490
make that a field trip there.

00:44:36.490 --> 00:44:39.435
It's really just hard to
find all of these things

00:44:39.435 --> 00:44:40.060
under one roof.

00:44:40.060 --> 00:44:42.610
And not only to find,
for instance, shiso,

00:44:42.610 --> 00:44:44.900
but to find five different
varieties of shiso.

00:44:44.900 --> 00:44:46.550
So you have options.

00:44:46.550 --> 00:44:49.286
They have 15 different
kinds of pineapple.

00:44:49.286 --> 00:44:52.604
It's like, who needs to choose
between 15 different kinds

00:44:52.604 --> 00:44:53.180
of pineapple?

00:44:53.180 --> 00:44:55.120
But if you're really
particular about the size

00:44:55.120 --> 00:44:58.190
and the level of acidity and
the country it comes from,

00:44:58.190 --> 00:45:03.210
if you want to shop with kind
of a social-justice conscience,

00:45:03.210 --> 00:45:05.690
then you can make your
selection and choose,

00:45:05.690 --> 00:45:08.760
I want a pineapple from this
country over that country.

00:45:08.760 --> 00:45:10.830
So no, I don't think
they have that.

00:45:10.830 --> 00:45:14.025
But my testers there, they
were really into farming,

00:45:14.025 --> 00:45:17.260
and so they grew a
lot of the stuff.

00:45:17.260 --> 00:45:20.166
They tested the cardoons
because cardoons also

00:45:20.166 --> 00:45:21.290
have a pretty short season.

00:45:21.290 --> 00:45:23.710
And so they even had those
growing in their garden,

00:45:23.710 --> 00:45:26.957
and they could test those.

00:45:26.957 --> 00:45:29.040
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: Laura,
what recipe in the book

00:45:29.040 --> 00:45:30.654
are you most proud of?

00:45:30.654 --> 00:45:32.320
I know that we talked
earlier, and there

00:45:32.320 --> 00:45:34.560
are some really
interesting ingredients

00:45:34.560 --> 00:45:36.860
that people might like to
hear more about and kind of

00:45:36.860 --> 00:45:39.984
how you got inspired to
come up with the recipes.

00:45:39.984 --> 00:45:41.650
LAURA MCLIVELY: Yeah,
I think the recipe

00:45:41.650 --> 00:45:44.410
I'm most proud of is--

00:45:44.410 --> 00:45:48.400
the example you used about your
wife-- the Indian bitter melon.

00:45:48.400 --> 00:45:53.210
So can raise your hand if you've
tried Indian bitter melon?

00:45:53.210 --> 00:45:54.730
OK, now keep your
hand up if you've

00:45:54.730 --> 00:45:57.100
liked Indian bitter melon.

00:45:57.100 --> 00:45:59.756
OK so we have, like,
eight people here.

00:45:59.756 --> 00:46:00.714
That's phenomenal.

00:46:00.714 --> 00:46:02.380
Usually, when I ask
that question, like,

00:46:02.380 --> 00:46:03.855
all the hands go down.

00:46:03.855 --> 00:46:05.940
So some people grew
up eating this.

00:46:05.940 --> 00:46:09.525
And it's really, really
good for you, I should say.

00:46:09.525 --> 00:46:11.170
It has really strong
anti-carcinogens

00:46:11.170 --> 00:46:13.180
and antioxidants in it.

00:46:13.180 --> 00:46:14.640
So I have patients
that will just

00:46:14.640 --> 00:46:16.372
blend this and kind
of plug their nose

00:46:16.372 --> 00:46:18.330
and drink it like a smoothie.

00:46:18.330 --> 00:46:20.560
But I wanted to find a
way to make it palatable.

00:46:20.560 --> 00:46:23.510
And the problem is
that I think when

00:46:23.510 --> 00:46:25.560
I heard that it was
bitter melon, I was like,

00:46:25.560 --> 00:46:26.827
OK, I like bitter.

00:46:26.827 --> 00:46:27.410
I like coffee.

00:46:27.410 --> 00:46:28.243
Yeah, I can do this.

00:46:28.243 --> 00:46:32.420
And I bit into it, and
it's not like coffee.

00:46:32.420 --> 00:46:36.410
To me, it really tastes
like ground-up aspirin,

00:46:36.410 --> 00:46:37.890
like really medicinal.

00:46:37.890 --> 00:46:42.340
And so it kind of made
my mouth go, like [GAG]..

00:46:42.340 --> 00:46:46.020
And so I tried to make
a curry and cover it up

00:46:46.020 --> 00:46:48.059
with a whole bunch of spices.

00:46:48.059 --> 00:46:49.850
That didn't work, so
then I was like, well,

00:46:49.850 --> 00:46:52.967
maybe I need coconut milk to
make it like a Thai cream.

00:46:52.967 --> 00:46:54.300
That will cover it up even more.

00:46:54.300 --> 00:46:55.258
And that made it worse.

00:46:55.258 --> 00:46:57.590
It's almost like the fat
drew out the bitterness.

00:46:57.590 --> 00:46:59.610
Then it was like Aspirin soup.

00:46:59.610 --> 00:47:01.870
And it was just a disaster.

00:47:01.870 --> 00:47:05.200
And so I persisted,
though, because I really

00:47:05.200 --> 00:47:07.084
wanted this ingredient
in the cookbook.

00:47:07.084 --> 00:47:08.500
Because it's, first
of all, really

00:47:08.500 --> 00:47:10.740
cool-looking, and also
very good for you.

00:47:10.740 --> 00:47:16.110
So then I just kind of changed
my course, my plan of attack.

00:47:16.110 --> 00:47:19.854
And I thought, I really should
try and go with the bitterness

00:47:19.854 --> 00:47:21.270
rather than trying
to cover it up.

00:47:21.270 --> 00:47:24.120
And so I thought
of things that I

00:47:24.120 --> 00:47:26.530
like that have that
same medicinal quality,

00:47:26.530 --> 00:47:28.770
and I thought of tonic.

00:47:28.770 --> 00:47:30.330
Because I love gin tonics.

00:47:30.330 --> 00:47:33.907
And tonic water has that
quinine, that kind of, like,

00:47:33.907 --> 00:47:35.990
bitterness to it, that if
you were to just have it

00:47:35.990 --> 00:47:38.860
on its own, it might not taste
that great, but in a tonic,

00:47:38.860 --> 00:47:40.140
it's wonderful.

00:47:40.140 --> 00:47:42.540
So I experimented with
recipes, and I ultimately

00:47:42.540 --> 00:47:45.750
came up with a homemade
tonic that you can

00:47:45.750 --> 00:47:47.456
make using Indian bitter melon.

00:47:47.456 --> 00:47:52.096
And you do it with grapefruit
and lemon and juniper berries.

00:47:52.096 --> 00:47:54.440
And it makes this
distilled tonic

00:47:54.440 --> 00:47:55.820
that you can keep
in your fridge.

00:47:55.820 --> 00:47:58.450
And you can just pour
it with some club soda

00:47:58.450 --> 00:48:00.930
and ice for a
non-alcoholic drink,

00:48:00.930 --> 00:48:03.500
or it's really good
as a gin tonic.

00:48:03.500 --> 00:48:06.430
And actually, one
of the sous chefs

00:48:06.430 --> 00:48:09.420
here came to one of my
talks at Omnivore Bookstore,

00:48:09.420 --> 00:48:10.830
and we served it there.

00:48:10.830 --> 00:48:13.735
So one person has had that,
at least, but I hope--

00:48:13.735 --> 00:48:16.110
whoever wants to take these
two home and try that recipe,

00:48:16.110 --> 00:48:19.071
you're welcome to.

