LAURA MCLIVELY: Do
you have picky kids?

00:48:34.464 --> 00:48:35.110
AUDIENCE: No.

00:48:35.110 --> 00:48:36.485
LAURA MCLIVELY:
So she asked what

00:48:36.485 --> 00:48:40.300
are my tips on introducing
these things to picky eaters.

00:48:40.300 --> 00:48:41.940
Oh, did I just turn off my mic?

00:48:41.940 --> 00:48:44.080
We're good, OK.

00:48:44.080 --> 00:48:46.210
So I have a six-month
old, so I, unfortunately,

00:48:46.210 --> 00:48:48.810
don't have quite a
lot of experience

00:48:48.810 --> 00:48:51.000
in feeding my kid
with these things,

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:53.290
or feeding my kid these
things, because she just

00:48:53.290 --> 00:48:53.980
started to eat.

00:48:53.980 --> 00:48:57.780
So we're on the sweet
potato level right now.

00:48:57.780 --> 00:49:01.690
But I think food is
all about the attitude

00:49:01.690 --> 00:49:02.740
that you serve it with.

00:49:02.740 --> 00:49:06.670
And again, even adults
can have a hard time

00:49:06.670 --> 00:49:08.830
looking at something
new and seeing it

00:49:08.830 --> 00:49:11.740
in the context of
their own kitchen.

00:49:11.740 --> 00:49:15.440
So I think it's just about
going with the attitude of fun

00:49:15.440 --> 00:49:16.300
and discovery.

00:49:16.300 --> 00:49:18.895
And I actually, at one
of my books signings,

00:49:18.895 --> 00:49:23.020
a French mom came up to me with
her, like, 10-year-old son,

00:49:23.020 --> 00:49:26.110
and she's like, my son never
wanted to eat vegetables,

00:49:26.110 --> 00:49:28.970
but we got your book, and he's
treating like his project.

00:49:28.970 --> 00:49:30.580
So he had all the
pages earmarked,

00:49:30.580 --> 00:49:33.290
and he'd written notes
in the columns of, like,

00:49:33.290 --> 00:49:37.167
"buy agave" and things that he
wanted to remind himself to do.

00:49:37.167 --> 00:49:39.500
And she said they cooked their
way through eight recipes

00:49:39.500 --> 00:49:42.580
already, and that he was really
excited because it was kind

00:49:42.580 --> 00:49:44.170
of like cool things, right?

00:49:44.170 --> 00:49:46.574
It's not like the typical
spinach and broccoli

00:49:46.574 --> 00:49:47.740
that his mom was giving him.

00:49:47.740 --> 00:49:51.040
So I think, like,
what kid wouldn't

00:49:51.040 --> 00:49:53.950
be excited about peeling this?

00:49:53.950 --> 00:49:56.090
If you involve your kids
in these sort of things,

00:49:56.090 --> 00:49:58.950
it can make it more fun.

00:49:58.950 --> 00:50:02.210
But yeah, I think just going
with that sense of discovery

00:50:02.210 --> 00:50:04.170
can make a big difference
for a picky eater.

